In the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it's time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank's boardroom, you'll see a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed chair, and her colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above everything else.
The central bank has been given a dual task by Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the U.S. and to maintain price stability.
But since the Great Depression, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the X factor in a decision that is too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is ready to be unleashed by the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect from the end of 2008.
Even though most data points to a strongly growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare off already cautious Fed officials from adding volatility by raising the federal funds rate - even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will be looking at", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
'I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the world market is enough to give them reason to wait,' she said.
There is no consensus on the decision the Fed will make, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg anticipated an interest rate increase this week.
But the financial markets expect the Fed to postpone a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a drop in the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policy makers soften the blow by promising it would be a long time until the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The surge was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising if the Fed raised interest rates at this time", Lonski said.
If the Fed's decision makers did this, they would have to act in-depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.
Other experts said that an interest rate increase would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed about to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected an interest rate hike this year despite objections from liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest rate in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers as total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And although inflation continued to fall short of the central bank's annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of plummeting oil prices.
The economy is facing higher rates and needs them, given the strain on the labour market, said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to vibrate later this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 16% below its record high in May, as investors feared that the slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed decision makers, market turbulence is added to the complex calculation of the momentum of the interest rate rise.
"Without what happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be firmer at the meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now, he predicts they'll wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy and they have almost no data to base themselves on after the events in China", Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed's major interests, so it should basically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been enormous.
The mere hint by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "tighten" its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in markets worldwide.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly entangled, it is expected that Fed officials not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at the well-being management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that the Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in the financial market that seem to have no bearing on the economic fundamentals.
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, the decision-making body that supported the interest rate increase, gave as an example the decisions of 1998-99.
A financial crisis affecting Asia led the Fed to reduce the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, despite the implications for U.S. development that could be identified only in limited ways, Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should only put financial stability first in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate-setting committee.
The last turbulent period is nowhere near that level, he said.
"We certainly don't want to be in a situation where we fear an interest rate rise because the markets are upset", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until something changes in that regard, I don't think it should take any premature action.
