Weight-loss surgery could be useful for mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes could be sustained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight-loss surgery than those who are on nonsurgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data", said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss surgeries, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in morbidly obese individuals with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or greater.
BMI, a unit of measurement of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range of 18,5 to 24,9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with a BMI of over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in mildly obese people.
The average BMI of surgeons decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of people who received non-surgical diabetes treatment remained close to the same level, at 29.
Of those who had surgery, 36% and 28% had partial diabetes.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, only 1% of the subjects had complete and only 2% partial diabetes recovery.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and LDL cholesterol control were generally better in the surgical group, the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored the blood level of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal hemoglobin A1c level is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin A1c level decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the treatment group, it remained at about 8 percent.
But this improved glycemic control - reflected in improved hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes associated with the two types of surgery.
At the fifth year, compared with the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), had more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%) and had a higher probability of complete diabetes remission (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who had bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who had surgery, Blackstone said it is optimistic for people with BMI under 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is where this paper is critical, because it says that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group", she says, "without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease".
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
'I think we're waiting too long to get people to take this seriously,' she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have shorted their bodies and made them prone to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely difficult to get back to normal.
