Quadrupling of children who ingested hand detergent in the last 4 years
According to the Georgia Poison Control Center, U.S. poison control centers have reported an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under 12 years of age who swallowed hand detergent with a high alcohol content.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, cases of children under 12 years of age ingesting hand detergent reported to poison control centers have risen from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children have more frequent access to these products and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up in the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said that some kids drink detergent intentionally and others do it to impress their friends or to respond to social media challenges.
You can watch videos on YouTube showing teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap beverages.
It turns out that teenagers mixed mouthwash with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of detergent.
"A child doesn't think it's hurting him", says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types are perfumed.
Strawberry, grape, orange flavored hand detergents are the most appealing to children.
Hand detergent contains about 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's very concentrated", said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poisoning center at the University of Kansas Hospital, to Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, that's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-flavored hand-wash sprays at school, arrived at the emergency room to receive treatment.
She had an alcohol level of 179, twice the legal limit for an adult under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, the emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was stuttering and couldn't walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage, as the girl fell and hit her head from alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was scary", Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic products or wet wipes and to keep hand detergent out of children's reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand detergent containing an undeclared toxic ingredient.
The health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, which was specified as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth graders in upstate New York plotted to poison their teacher by putting antibacterial products in the classroom, according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and has banned it in her classroom.
The police considered the plan to be "insignificant" and referred the disciplinary matter to the school inspectorate.
