FriendsFest: the comedy series that taught us important lessons about male friendship
The absence of similar characters in the series is obvious, given that the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men reaching their highest in 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death among men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than women.
In an attempt to address the issue, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) has designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, seeking to challenge the culture that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the fight to succeed in this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students who had symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends  with a healthy mood, his chances of recovery double.
Similarly, for people who are not depressed, having a healthy circle of friends halves the likelihood of developing mental disorders.
Of course, for friendship to work, it must first be accessible.
In this age of social media-dominated communication, where the emphasis is on style rather than substance, the immediacy of the response often takes precedence over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong, fun-loving, successful personality, even though in reality isolation is the dominant one.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values -- money, image, social status -- all at the expense of intrinsic values -- our inner desire for personal growth and friendship -- that affect our mental health even more profoundly.
The billionaire video game inventor recently explained that money really doesn't buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that it drew attention to this idea.
The characters were not defined by their work, but by their personality, which they showed through their interaction as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments of watching football in comfortable chairs, and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that men are known to associate with this situation, even though they often shy away from fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me, my role in listening to suicidal and depressed people showed how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference.
Often, people who turn to us feel unable to talk to their friends.
The old saying of doing it yourself is powerful, as is the feeling of being perceived as weak if you talk openly about problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to provide more mechanisms for long-term psychological adaptation.
The show highlighted the little moments of friendship between men.
As much as objective, outside intervention, through the phone, helps people in desperate times, the long-term support comes from family and close friends.
So if you're at this weekend's FriendsFest by Comedy Central, with a full set of tapes to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends over for coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone at Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship might make.
