Thousands of people came to put a candle on it
Thousands of people passed by the coffin with the lifeless body of Cornelius Vadim Tudor, so many people did not come to the Church of St. George but to the consecration of his house at the Great Temple of St. Nicholas, said on Wednesday, parish priest Emil Caramizaru.
Hundreds of people of all ages wait in line, stretching from the church entrance to the side streets, to pass by the catacombs on which the coffin with the lifeless body of Cornelius Vadim Tudor is located.
People wait about an hour to reach the Church of St. George the New, where groups of up to 40 people enter.
About 300 people an hour passed by the coffin of Cornelius Vadim Tudor.
Thousands of people from Bucharest, but also from Cluj, Baia Mare, Iasi, Constanta and Craiova came, starting on Tuesday, to pay homage to Corneliu Vadim Tudor, so many people we had only at the 300th anniversary of the church and the Great Temple of St. Nicholas.
"Corneliu Vadim Tudor was at the 300th anniversary consecration of the church and sat next to the members of the Holy Synod, the Blessed Daniel and representatives of the five patriarchs who participated in the consecration", said the parish priest of the church in the capital, Emil Caramizaru.
According to him, people came with flowers and candles in hand, sitting neatly and waiting in line, as on a day of great religious celebration.
It's amazing how these people behave, they're all sitting there, with dignity, children, old people, people in their carriages, like they're at a big religious celebration.
"It is moving to see them waiting to bow and pay their last respects to Vadim Tudor", said Parish Priest Emil Caramizaru.
According to him, at the request of the family of Cornelius Vadim Tudor, the church will remain open on Wednesday and Thursday nights, last night being closed at 01:00 and reopened in the morning at 07:00.
He said that on Thursday morning at 10.00 a.m. in the Church of St. George, at kilometer 0, a short service will be held, after which the coffin with the body of Vadim Tudor will be transported to the civil cemetery of Ghencea, where the funeral service will take place, with a religious and military ceremony being officiated.
The priest insisted that Vadim Tudor would often come to this church, especially in the evening, after 8pm, and then he would ask him to open the fridge with the remains of St. Nicholas and stay for minutes to pray in the siren.
He used to come here very often, usually after 8pm, begging me to open his fridge with the relics of St. Nicholas and pray.
He said it's a great blessing this church of Brancoveanu.
He said to me, "Brother Emil, think that here were Brancoveanu, Eminescu, Michael the Hero, who held hands with St. Nicholas".
"'You can see what a blessing this country is,' Vadim would tell me", the parish priest related.
Cornelius Vadim Tudor is to be buried Thursday at the Ghencea Civil Cemetery with full military honors.
The Senate leadership on Tuesday rejected the request of the wife of Cornelius Vadim Tudor that the coffin containing the former senator's lifeless body be deposited in the hall of the Legislative Chamber.
Corneliu Vadim Tudor was born on 28 November 1949 in Bucharest, he was a writer, politician and journalist.
He was the founder of the Romania Mare Party, a former member of the European Parliament and a former senator.
