He added that after the activity report is rejected by the plenary, elections will be held for a new Board of Directors, which will elect the Director-General of the institution.
I don't know who's going to be nominated for this job.
Miracles will not happen.
It's important to make political decisions for this institution to function.
I'm not the man to lie to you, to tell you that a genius will appear who will stand in line here and fight.
I hope that those who decide, the plenary of Parliament, by their vote will choose with much reason the people who will lead TVR.
There must be people who know what's going on there, have experience and have a lot of fairness and respect for institution and tradition.
I don't know who he's going to be, if you ask me what qualities he has to have -- good sense in his attitude toward employees because it's a mess of petitions coming from employees, complaints, layoffs.
"When you get these 50, 60, 70 reports, something is rotten and we're talking about the financial situation that's a disaster", the chairman of the Senate culture committee concluded.
Although he did not appear in Parliament, TVR's President-General Stelian Tanase sent a letter to the President of the Chamber of Deputies, Valeriu Zgonea, asking the Parliament to consider a series of measures that could lead to the salvage and guarantee of the economic and political independence of public television, including the indexation of the TV tax.
In the letter, Stelian Tanase requested, in addition to the indexation of the TV fee, the amendment of HG 978/2003 on the public service television fee, in order to update the provisions on the level of technological changes on a daily basis, and to regulate the procedure for the control in the field of the payment of the TV fee and the detection of infringements and the application of penalties and penalties.
It also wants a provision to extend the obligation for all electricity suppliers to become agents of SRTv for the collection of the TV charge by involving ANRE in the regulation of this activity.
In its view, a maximum ceiling of 5% of the commission on receipts should be set.
Stelian Tanase is asking for the VAT rate for the specific activities of the public television station and the contribution for the CNC to be reduced from 15% to 3%, and also to amend Law 41/1994 to allow for the possibility of receiving budgetary/financial allocations for the purchase of licenses for major cultural and sporting events - the World Cup, the Golden Deer, Eurovision.
He argues that SRTv will become insolvent in the coming months given that labour law obliges the employer to enforce court decisions, even if they are not final, and that wage rights are honoured with priority over any other obligation.
The TVR administration has made constant efforts to reduce staff and TV production costs.
"Thus, travel and other cost-generating activities were reduced, a number of commercial contracts were renegotiated, and TVR News was closed at the end of July", the letter from TVR's president states.
Tanase believes that the financial disaster cannot be remedied by her own efforts.
'Without the support of the state institutions - the Government, Parliament, the Presidency - Romanian television will sooner or later be unable to fulfil its public mission,' the letter states.
The leadership of the Chamber of Deputies has decided to send the letter to the Committee on Culture.
Vasile Blaga's son-in-law, sent to court
Vasile Blaga's son-in-law, Ionut Andrei Rudeanu, was sent to trial on Wednesday by the prosecutors of the Prosecutor's Office near the Bucharest Court of Appeal.
He is accused of tax evasion, in a case involving damages of approximately 600,000 euros, and is under judicial control.
