Ponta, accused of uncontrolled slander and irrational statements
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto strongly condemned on Wednesday morning the statements of Romanian Prime Minister Victor Ponta that Hungary's political decision-makers are "no better than those in Syria, Libya or other countries from which refugees flee".
"Yesterday, Victor Ponta lost his temper and, with his irrational statements, is insulting the whole of Hungary", the Hungarian Foreign Minister said in a statement.
Civilized European politicians don't say such uncontrolled slanders.
"His remarks have only one explanation: he has completely lost support in Romania's domestic politics", the Hungarian foreign minister added, according to MTI.
In a Facebook post on Tuesday evening, Prime Minister Victor Ponta said he wanted to draw attention to and sanction the behavior of some high-ranking Hungarian government officials, who he said "are a disgrace to the culture and values of the European Union".
I do not wish to respond to the challenges from some representatives of the Hungarian government.
"They are a disgrace to the culture and values of the European Union; and to anti-Semitic attitudes, and to the treatment of minorities of all kinds, and now during the refugee crisis!" Ponta wrote on Facebook.
The Romanian Prime Minister added that he is in favour of rational and sustainable solutions to the refugee crisis, believing that brutality and aggressive laws will not solve the problem.
The rigged wire, aggressive laws, prisons and brutality will certainly not solve the problem - they will only show that in Hungary, in the heart of Europe, there are no better political decision-makers than those in Syria, Libya or other countries from which the respective refugees are fleeing!
"I believe in solidarity, in rational and sustainable solutions and above all in the superiority of European values - what we have seen in Hungary in recent days is in total contradiction with these very objectives and values!" the Romanian chief executive stressed.
Earlier on Tuesday, Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto called Romanian Prime Minister Victor Ponta's remarks about Hungary's handling of the refugee crisis "simple lies", saying such statements were inappropriate for a 21st-century leader, according to MTI.
The Hungarian foreign minister also mentioned on Tuesday that the Romanian prime minister's "extremist and lying remarks" were related to the internal political crisis in Romania and said that Budapest expects an apology from the Romanian side.
Szijjarto was referring to a statement made by Prime Minister Victor Ponta on Monday.
What I've said and I've always said is that I'm against xenophobic rhetoric, the idea of closing borders, that everyone who comes in is a terrorist, is a medieval fool, and I'm totally against that approach.
If we can get more, we will, the problem is our logistical ability to treat those people as human beings, not as they treat our neighbors, the Hungarians, with the bat and the sunset.
"I don't agree with that", the Romanian chief executive said at a press conference in Targu-Jiu.
