At 20 years old, he received a courageous gift: biological parents.
Lost in a hospital under unclear conditions in the gloom of the '90s, when she was only two months old, small, sick and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same years when adoption was loosely regulated, a young Ischia, now a beautiful blonde girl, was reunited the other day in Iaşi with her birth parents from a rural county, after almost two decades in which nobody knew anything about the others.
Crina will be 20 years old today, and her adoptive parents in Palermo have thought of giving their beloved daughter an amazing and courageous gift: a visit to Romania, to Iași, to learn about her obscure past.
The "Gazette de Iasi", which witnessed the search for the family of origin after some extremely vague clues, witnessed these meetings that practically break your heart.
The reporting by the reporters, the emotions of the moment, the statements of those involved, their reactions are truly moving and overwhelming.
Crina's story begins 20 years ago in the Ionian town of Ruginoasa, when she was only two months old.
Then, because of a health problem, the girl had to be admitted to the hospital in the city.
At home, there began to be disagreements between the parents, and Mother was forced to leave home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away.
He stopped the girl, and I didn't know anything since.
"When I found out that she was in the hospital, it was too late", recalls Alina, the girl's biological mother, in mourning.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pashkani, and at the same time the girl's father, Costica Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman County.
Their lives were about to be forever separated.
They never found Crina at the hospital.
After the internment, Crina's father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iasi, and when her father returned, he could not find her.
I think it was almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"She must have thought she was abandoned", says one of the family's granddaughters.
Due to financial problems, Grandma could not come with Crina to Iasi, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Because no one was interested in the child's fate during this time, she was taken over by the Directorate General of Social Assistance and Child Protection of Iaşi, which then gave her to the care of the Placement Center in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were less regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Center she was found by the Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but could not.
They immediately fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after a while she would move permanently with them to Italy.
The little girl was almost two years old when the adoption formalities took place.
When we saw Crina, we felt like she was our girl.
"It was as if my wife had given birth to her", says smiling Salvadore, the adoptive father, as he grabs the girl's hands in his palm.
In the country, Crina's parents, Alina and Costica, continued their searches separately, each where they could.
The father asked the authorities in Ruginoasa, but received no answer where his child might be.
The police then told her that she might have died, but in Iaşi the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me at the courthouse that she'd gone to Italy, to Palermo.
And the conditions to look for her I didn't have.
We prayed to God that he would be well.
I've thought about it all these years, but there's been no chance for us to walk around, to find it.
"It's hard", Crina's birth mother tells us with tears in her eyes.
But even as the years passed, the parents of Ruginoasa were not forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past linked her to Romania.
I was a little girl when I found out.
I think I was five or six.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to meet my Romanian parents", says happy Crina.
And her dream was about to come true.
In March of this year, Chief Commissioner Ichim Romică, director of the Regional Centre for Prevention, Evaluation and Counselling against Drugs Iași, was contacted by an acquaintance in Italy, who explained to him Salvadore's desire to find Crine's biological family.
And the search started with just one name.
Following the request from our Italian partners, we started the first steps.
We'd just gotten a name, Balkan Costic, then the locality, Rust.
Soon I had an activity with the city hall there, and I could ask if there was a name received locally.
Then they gave me some clues, only the person they found wasn't the one they were looking for.
"It took about a month to find the girl's biological father", explains Chief Commissioner Ichim.
In all, it took the authorities more than three months to find Costica and Alina, especially since they were living in different localities.
We started the process in March, and in June-July, we finished identifying the biological parents and the discussions.
"Then we arranged for a first meeting in September", Roman Ichim added.
Last weekend, Alina and Costica saw their daughter for the first time, lost in the halls of the hospital in Iaşi 20 years ago.
The father was so moved that he could hardly hold back his tears, and his hands were constantly shaking.
He barely exchanges a few words with the people around him.
A week before the meeting, he couldn't sleep.
He was all excited, shaking.
"To see your child after all these years is something", says a granddaughter, who also came with Costica from Ruginoasa.
Crina meets her mother and biological brother
In his discussions with his daughter, who is going to study at a top-ranked university in Italy, Costica Balcan told her, among other things, that if she ever wanted to return to him in the village, she should come quietly: she could give him some sheep, goats, so that she could find a boy in the village and start a household.
My mother is also very emotional, crying, and she can hardly believe that this could happen to her.
I'm very excited.
I never thought this could happen.
I've seen cases like this on TV, I've been thinking about it all these years, I've been hoping, but I never thought I could be like this.
There are very big emotions.
If they could forgive me.
I hope we can visit in the future.
"I hope we can keep in touch", says Alina, Crina's mother, with tears in her eyes, as she holds a napkin tightly in her hand.
In it she hides her tears of joy, for soon she will see her face after so bitter a time.
On the other hand, Crina, who will be 20 in just a few days this month, is trying to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn't know what to expect, but she's sketched out a vague idea about her biological parents.
He thinks they're young, but now before the meeting he tries to gather his thoughts, because he has so much to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two moms and two dads.
But my parents are the ones who raised me after all.
It's going to be a beautiful meeting, a wonderful experience.
"I hope I have a good memory of them, because there is so much to tell now", says Crina.
First family reunion in Iaşi
In the Piazza dell'Unità, under the sky of early autumn, the family from Ruginoasa reunites their destiny with their daughter from Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, finishing high school, following the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
There are no longer borders or countries, only a barrier: the barrier of language.
And with the help of a translator, an Italian who owns a place in the center of Iaşi, they got through it with ease.
Those who have made this meeting possible say that it is the first event of its kind ever held, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do it again.
It's the first event of its kind organized, with such an emotional load, and I'm glad it's a success.
We at the Centre have different activities, and we are often associated as an institution that deals only with people who use drugs, people who are addicted to drugs.
But we're trying to give society something good back.
"If I am asked to participate in such an event again, I will gladly do so", says Romika Ichim, director of the Regional Center for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling in Iaşi, smiling.
Behind him, the Balkan family, with Crina in the middle, parting ways telling their stories.
They're understandable: they have a lot to say to each other.
