Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in recent decades cannot continue in the years to come.
Until Saturday probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn was.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the Labour Party in Britain, many are wondering how much the election of a politician who is not in a decision-making position can affect us.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical left-wing Labour leader since the war.
An avowed Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once urged Tony Blair, then prime minister, to remove the royal family from Buckingham Palace), a fierce anti-American and a supporter of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events by the "Russia Today" television channel), and of the terrorist movements Hezbollah and Hamas, he wants Britain to give up nuclear weapons and leave NATO and the EU.
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a real tragedy, ISIS is almost the preferred choice of the United States.
Following the pattern of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
The kind of things that Tsipras said and promised in Greece until he faced the real world and economic legitimacy.
The new Labour leader's economic programme includes massive re-nationalization and printing money as a solution to finance development projects and cover very generous social benefits.
Sure, some might wonder why the solution of printing money is not adopted unanimously around the globe, we would then have a global general prosperity!, but who would be stumbled by such details.
Sure, we can tax the bankers on blood, you become a kind of enemy of the left, but as we've seen so many times in the past, not just in the former communist states or Ecuador or Venezuela, but in France, at the beginning of the Mitterrand and Hollande mandates.
The extra money is quickly swallowed up by the generous, uncovered promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher so aptly pointed out, "the problem with socialism is that at some point you run out of other people's money".
Few give Jeremy Corbyn any real chance of ever becoming Prime Minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in convictions as the new party leader, failed miserably in the election.
And then there was still a working class in Britain, in the classic sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were considerably more influential than they are now.
In the new industrial landscape, where services dominate the workforce as a whole and extensive automation has led to a massive need for highly skilled labour in industry, Corbyn's rhetoric has limited appeal.
But even from opposition, he can influence important developments that can affect us directly.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that Corbyn's election increases the chances of Brexit, or Britain leaving the EU.
The new Labour leader has been a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalisation that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine this kind of thinking with the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and you look at the refugee crisis that is shaking the foundations of the EU, you get an explosive mix.
And not just for Britain.
But if the British decide, following the referendum, which is due to take place by 2017, to leave the Union, the symbolic loss of capital for the whole European project and the deep rifts created within it by the Euro crisis and now by the refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leaves room for the most worrying scenarios.
Moreover, for a whole series of Member States, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin is becoming increasingly the dominant player).
It's true, the British business community, the City, are strong advocates of the country staying in the EU.
But Europe today is not the same as it was in the past.
There are many resentments, which are growing in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, we had a sample of it even recently in Jean Clude Juncker's speech, tends increasingly to take major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of Member States in consultation with only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening at a time when electoral support for anti-establishment, anti-immigration and eurosceptic groups is growing dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the emotional climate with negative charges has reached higher rates than at any time in the past.
Hence the conclusion that the Financial Times draws when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation that departs from the national interest.
If the voters make the decision in their heads, then Britain will stay in the EU.
But Corbyn's victory reminds us of the power of emotion in politics today.
Eastern Europe may be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as is to be expected, we see a more pronounced integration of the euro area, which will push most of the states in the region to the periphery of the interest and decision-making process in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States are fueling their populist rhetoric from the accumulated frustrations of Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in recent decades, the generous social benefits, cannot continue in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, Euro-zone - immigration, both caused by hasty decisions that have taken into account only integrationist political ambitions, not the capacity and readiness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and may affect the situation of Romania more.
And it's hard to rule anything out in terms of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are capable of dealing with such complicated situations.
